The Federal Ministry of Health (FMoH) has confirmed five new cases of the coronavirus in Nigeria within the last 36 hours. This is bringing total number of confirmed cases in Nigeria to 8. The minister of health, Dr. E. Osagie Ehanire, in a statement Wednesday morning, revealed three from the new positive cases arrived from the United States, while two came in from the United Kingdom. The Nigeria Centre for Disease Control (NCDC) had earlier tweeted about the new five cases. @Fmohnigeria has announced 5 new cases of #COVID19 in Nigeria bringing the total number confirmed cases in Nigeria to 8 All 5 cases had a travel history to the UK/USA We urge Nigerians to remain calm as public health response activities are intensified across the country pic.twitter.com/yoKLHXoxhq â€” NCDC (@NCDCgov) March 18, 2020  Two of the three from the US are Nigerians, a mother and child, making the 6 week old baby the youngest coronavirus patient in the country. The third is an American national, who crossed the land border, making him the first coronavirus case not arriving by air. The two other cases from the UK are Nigerians. The recent coronavirus case reported on Tuesday was a Nigerian woman who returned from the United Kingdom on March 13th. The second case of the virus was one of the persons who had close contact with the first reported case- an Italian engineer. The Italian citizen worked in Nigeria and returned from Milan, Italy to Lagos on the 25th of February. Address Nigerians on coronavirus, Senate tells Buhari FG: No need to panic over new coronavirus cases Coronavirus: Nigerians panic as FG issues red alert